Finding best number of clusters by my own measure - explanation¶

In order to choose the best number of groups I will subjectively divide 10 points for each considered number of clusters, looking only at the measures. I intend to consider two unsupervised learning algorithms (KMeans and Agglomerative Clustering) and three measures (elbow method only for KMeans, Silhoutte score, DaviesBouldin index), so all candidates in total will get 50 points - 30 points for the first algorithm, and 20 points for the second. Finally, I will make this podium from both thirtes, all the points after adding up and compare it with the intuition of the eye.

First algorithm - KMeans¶

Let's check probably the most famous clustering algorithm and visualize the effects for the six parameters mentioned above.

In [11]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

def kmeans_and_plot_3d(X, n):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n, random_state = 17)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    y_means = kmeans.predict(X)
    
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
    ax.scatter3D(X['X2'], X['X3'], X['X1'], c = y_means)
    ax.set_title('KMeans clustering: ' + str(n) + " clusters")
    ax.set_xlabel('X2')
    ax.set_ylabel('X3')
    ax.set_zlabel('X1')

    return y_means

Best cluster rating: elbow method¶

Wow! Didn't even know elbow means okie in polish.

In [14]:
def count_wcss_scores(X, clusters_range):
    scores = []
    for n in clusters_range:
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n, random_state = 617)
        kmeans.fit(X)
        wcss = kmeans.score(X) * -1
        scores.append(wcss)
    return scores
In [15]:
wcss_vec = count_wcss_scores(df, n_of_clusters)
x_ticks = list(n_of_clusters)
plt.plot(x_ticks, wcss_vec, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within-cluster sum of squares')
plt.title('The Elbow Method showing the optimal k')
plt.show()

In this case it's pretty unclear to decide which cluster is the best - 3, 4 or maybe 6. It's pretty satisfying after my first thought.

After seeing this plot, I give: 4 points for n = 6, 3 points for n = 3 and 3 points for n = 4.

Best cluster rating: Silhouette score¶

In [17]:
def count_clustering_scores(X, cluster_num, model, score_fun):
    if isinstance(cluster_num, int):
        cluster_num_iter = [cluster_num]
    else:
        cluster_num_iter = cluster_num
        
    scores = []    
    for k in cluster_num_iter:
        model_instance = model(n_clusters=k)
        labels = model_instance.fit_predict(X)
        wcss = score_fun(X, labels)
        scores.append(wcss)
    
    if isinstance(cluster_num, int):
        return scores[0]
    else:
        return scores
In [18]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette score')
plt.show()

Wow, so huge hole between 2 & 3 and the others!

After seeing this, I give: 5 points for n = 3, 4 points for n = 2 and 1 point for n = 6.

Second algorithm - Agglomerative Clustering¶

In [27]:
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
In [28]:
agg_models = [0] * 6
agg_ys = [0] * 6

for n in n_of_clusters:
    agg_models[n-min_clusters] = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = n, linkage = 'ward')
    agg_ys[n-min_clusters] = agg_models[n-min_clusters].fit_predict(df)
    
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
    ax.scatter3D(df['X2'], df['X3'], df['X1'], c = agg_ys[n-min_clusters])
    ax.set_title('Agglomerative clustering: ' + str(n) + " clusters")
    ax.set_xlabel('X2')
    ax.set_ylabel('X3')
    ax.set_zlabel('X1')

Ok, so in most cases the effect is similar to the use of KMeans ... But damn it, n = 4 this time is the most intuitive!! Another thing that we could actually expect from the nature of our dataset.

Which method did better?¶

Without a doubt - Agglomerative clustering! Just look at this n = 4!! But... why did neither of the technices approved its operations?

The conclusion is simple - even using a few metrics will not always give us a picture that reflects reality - two random methods are definitely not enough and you have to either use them much more wisely knowing the consequences, or do excellent visualizations that answer the question about the number of clusters.
